h3. Issue Summary
In an instance which is not in the control group (have the new editing experience for *Blog Posts*/*Meeting notes* and the option to *Try the new editing experience*), it is not possible to create a page from the Meeting Notes template. It opens the template, but on the old editor and it is not possible to edit the page.

h3. Environment
* Cloud

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# On an instance which is not in the control group, create a page from the Meeting Notes template;
# Then, proceed with the below actions:
* Try to add or remove rows or columns on the table;
* Try adding a new table to the page;
* Try the Delete Unpublished Page.

h3. Expected Results
The Meeting notes template should open in the new editing experience and save the page. Also, according to the respective above actions:
* Let you add/remove rows/columns in the existing table;
* Let you add a new table;
* Let you delete the unpublished meeting notes page.

h3. Actual Results
The old editor is loaded with the template and the "Can't save changes" status is shown. When you try to perform those mentioned actions:
* No cloumns/rows can be added/deleted;
* You cannot add a new table;
* You are unable to delete the page and after a while, it returns a "no access to this page" warning message.

h3. Workaround
After opening the Meeting Notes template, even it showing us "Can't save changes", publish the page and then go to edit it. It will allow you to edit the page as you wish.

h3. The situation:
* You have a space called "*The Space*" favorited, so it appears into the *My Spaces* section, at the dashboard;
* A time has been passed and you realized that *The Space* should be archived;
* You archive *The Space*;
* Once you back to your Dashboard, you are still able to see the archived space in your favorites list.

h3. The Suggestion:
When we archive a space, it gets removed from the My Spaces list, unfavoriting the space at the moment it is archived.

h3. Issue Summary
On an instance which doesn't have the new editing experience, some templates are coming with instructions only applied to the new editor (mostly of them instructing the customer to use *slash* instead of *keys* to call macros. The affected templates are listed below:
* Decision;
* How-to;
* Marketing Plan;
* Persona;
* Product Launch;
* Product Requirements;
* Product Plan;
* Retrospective;
* Troubleshooting Article.

h3. Environment
 * Cloud

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Go to any space and create a page from one of the previously listed templates;
# The tips inside the template instruct the user to use "/jira", for example, to call a JIRA macro, instead of "{jira".

h3. Expected Results
Correct instructions according to the editor version which the user has in his/her instance.

h3. Actual Results
Incompatible instructions with the editor version are being shown to the user.

h3. Workaround
Currently there is no known workaround for this behavior. A workaround will be added here when available

h3. Summary

Exporting a page to PDF, that contains a "Columns" macro with two or more columns and containing one or more tables, will result in truncated tables (mainly on the left margin of the table).
h3. Environment
 * "Columns" macro with two or more columns;
 * A Table;
 * New Confluence Editor.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Insert into a page a "Columns" macro, select two columns;
 # Insert a table into the page (even a single column table will do);
 # Publish the page
 # Click (*...*) drop-down menu > *Export to PDF*

!Screen Shot 2019-04-10 at 11.01.28.png|thumbnail!
h3. Expected Results
 * PDF file should reproduce the same formatting as the original document.

h3. Actual Results
 * Tables are truncated on the left margin, as can be seen in the next screenshot.

 !Exported PDF.png|thumbnail! 

h3. Notes
 * There were some suggestions on other tickets regarding editing the PDF stylesheet on Space Settings, but I've tried the following workarounds but none of them worked to circumvent this BUG.

{code:CSS}
@page
{
/*A4-sized pages in landscape orientation are 297 mm wide by 210 mm long*/
size: 297mm 210mm;
}
{code}
{code:CSS}
table
{
   table-layout:auto !important;
   width: auto !important;
   max-width: 90% !important
} {code}
{code:CSS}
table
{
   table-layout:auto !important;
   width: auto !important;
}{code}
h3. Workaround
 * Paste this on the space settings for PDF stylesheet
{code}
@page {
 size: 210mm 297mm; /* A4, change for US letter */
 margin: 18mm 20mm;
}
div.wiki-content {
 width: 150mm !important;
 align-self: center !important;
 margin: 20px 30mm 20px 20px !important;
 line-height: 1.4 !important
}{code}
